# UI, Content, and Agent Governance

## 1) UI design language (always enforce)
- Use one coherent visual system per page: shared spacing scale, border radii, typography, and color tokens.
- Avoid "marketing wall" layouts. Prioritize information hierarchy and readability over CTA density.
- New UI work must pass: responsive behavior, keyboard focus visibility, and sufficient contrast.
- If a page is editorial (daily report), tone must be newsroom/analyst style, not ad copy.

## 2) Report content standards (daily editions)
- Every edition must include: `headline`, `direction`, `sentiment`, `what changed`, and `why it matters`.
- Free tier must still be useful and readable, not empty teaser blocks.
- Subscriber blocks may hide depth, but must provide a clear preview of what is inside.
- Avoid em-dash-heavy writing in UI copy; use plain punctuation for natural newsroom style.

## 3) Traceability and retrieval
- Every report edition must be date-addressable (`asof`) and timestamped (`generated_at`).
- Persist report snapshots for lookback retrieval and subscriber history views.
- If a fact/metric/news item is shown, include source-attributable context where available.

## 4) LLM and tool-call discipline
- LLMs may summarize, extract, and narrate; they do not compute CRS, edge, EV, or distance math.
- For extraction/scoring prompts, require structured JSON outputs and deterministic parsing guards.
- Web-searched claims must be tied to source + as-of time before display in reports.
- If data is missing or stale, report missingness explicitly; do not fabricate certainty.

## 5) Delivery checklist for UI/report changes
- Update page content to be useful for free users before adding upsell copy.
- Remove outdated/duplicated disclaimers and low-trust filler language.
- Run diagnostics and basic runtime checks after edits.
- Keep improvements consistent across main dashboard, daily report page, and stock report pages.
